# Competitive Intelligence (CI) Dashboard
**TELUS · Senior AI Product Manager · 2024 – Present**

---

## The problem

TELUS's competitive intelligence process was entirely manual: team members scraping competitor websites by hand, copying data into spreadsheets, and sharing updates inconsistently. The result: the team was capturing only 10–15% of actual market activity, the data was often stale by the time it reached decision-makers, and the process was unsustainable because it depended entirely on whoever happened to be assigned to it that week.

The "8-month rotation reset" was a real operational failure mode — every time the person doing CI rotated off, institutional knowledge walked out the door with them.

---

## My role

I took ownership of a fragmented, "side-of-the-desk" activity and productized it into a scalable enterprise tool. This was not a planned product when I joined — I identified it as a gap, built the case, and drove it from pilot to TELUS-wide deployment.

---

## What I built

An automated, AI-powered competitive intelligence platform using GenAI and multimodal extraction to monitor competitor pricing, offers, and promotions in near real time.

**Phased adoption strategy I designed:**

| Phase | Scope | Rationale |
|---|---|---|
| Phase 1 | Bell and Videotron (primary competitors) | Build trust with high-signal data before expanding |
| Phase 2 | Flanker brands | Extend to secondary competitive set |
| Phase 3 | EPP (Employee Purchase Plans) | Complex: required handling login-gated competitor pages |
| Phase 4 | Physical Channel Monitoring | AI integration for in-store competitive coverage |

The phasing was deliberate. Starting with the most trusted data source (primary competitors) built organizational confidence in the tool before asking stakeholders to rely on it for edge cases.

---

## Key product decisions

**From raw data to actionable alerts:** Early users found the raw data too complex to act on. I pushed the engineering team to implement "From-to" pricing alerts — actionable summaries of what changed and by how much, rather than raw price point data. This was a usability decision that drove adoption.

**Black Friday War Room:** I recognized that standard daily scraping was insufficient during peak retail periods. On November 21, 2025, I launched a specialized Black Friday Dashboard with hourly scraping from 5AM to 9PM — giving TELUS real-time parity with competitor moves during the highest-stakes retail week of the year.

**Physical channel expansion:** By identifying that digital channels accounted for only 15% of the team's total competitive monitoring workload, I positioned the project for its most valuable phase: AI-integrated monitoring of physical retail pricing — which has never been automated at scale.

---

## Stakeholder crisis I resolved

In March 2026, a critical stakeholder (director-level) refused to sign off on $102K in Q1 benefits, citing low daily usage figures and a disagreement with the FTE savings methodology.

**What I did not do:** Retreat, escalate to my manager, or let the project stall.

**What I did:** Scheduled a deep-dive methodology walkthrough directly with the stakeholder. In that session, I addressed the usage concern by identifying a massive unmet opportunity — Physical Channel Expansion — that the skeptic had not considered. I turned a potential program cancellation into a validated Q2 roadmap. The stakeholder signed off.

This is the kind of situation that kills AI products at enterprise companies. It requires the PM to stay in the room and reframe, not just defend.

